The ſecond to Reube • , whom that famous Proteſtation concerning the Altar of Witneſſe built at the banke of Iordan enobled;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . Ioſua 22. 21. whereby he deſerved that he ſhould not ſubmit his birth-right
(for he was the firſt borne) to any other then Iuda the kingly tribe. Chap. 7.

By theſe three, fire, ſmoake, and brimſtone iſſuing out of guns, Verſe 9. he addeth, that the third part of men are killed, that is, they which were of that third part of men, whom wee called the Roman Empire. Neither is it neceſſary here of elſe-where, whre mention is of a third part, that the whole third part be underſtood, but to be taken partitively. Examples offer themſelves as well in this book as elſewhere in the Scripture of ſuch an Ellipſis of a word partitive: as Iudges 12. 7. Iephte was buried in the Cities of Gilead, that is, in one of the Cities. And Rev. 17. 16. The tenne hornes ſhall hate the whore, that is ſome of them. So the third part of men was killed (
                                 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                              ) that is they which were of the third part.

The Targum upon the 50. Pſalme, the 8. verſ. The Iuſt ſhall ſay (
                        〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                     ) in the day of the great Iudgement: Our God ſhall come, and ſhall not keepe ſilence, that he may revenge his people.
